@missionz3r0 Hi, we suggested using string type value for the id and name property. If you are using `number` type, echarts will guess it's an index because index has a higher priority. You can use `string` type instead.
```js
data = [{
    id: 'n1',
    name: 'n1',
  }, {
    id: 'n2',
    name: 'n2',
  }];

edges = [{
    source: 'n1',
    target: 'n2'
}];
```

BTW I found the English doc is not as clear as Chinese doc about these properties. We will fix that.

I think I have found the cause.  The problem seems to be in the `turnPointsIntoStep` func in [LineView.js](https://github.com/apache/incubator-echarts/blob/fd064123626c97b36cbd6da1b5fc73385c280abd/src/chart/line/LineView.js#L189)

The function automatically grabs the next point without checking if any of the point coordinates are NaN - which ends up with a bad point array.

The way I see it this can be fixed in two ways - 
1. We can sanitize the points array at the beginning of the function by filtering all NaN values. 
Something like this would do it:
`points = points.filter((el) => !isNaN(el[0]) && !isNaN(el[1]));` 

2. In the actual for-loop we can skip over NaN elements until we get the next well-defined point. 
```
 for (var i = 0; i < points.length - 1; i++) {
        var pt = points[i];
        // Skip over undefined points.
        while (isNaN(points[i + 1][0]) || isNaN(points[i + 1][1])) {
            i++;
        }
        var nextPt = points[i + 1];

```
Running a dev build locally - and testing with the reproduction code I posted above seems to result in a nice step line. 

Let me know which way you think is more suitable or if there's something I'm missing. 
I'm happy to raise a PR and add tests if necessary.

